1S 2D 2H Pass 2S Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\S. East overcalls 2\d.  What do you bid?[BID 2H]
After East's 2\D overcall both North and South know that the 2/1 Game Force in no longer on. South can therefore bid 2\H, showing at least 11 points. This bid is forcing on North for 1 round, but not forcing to game.
North next rebids his \Ss, promising a 6-card suit, but also indicating a minimum strength hand. Since the Game Force is not on, North would have to make a jump bid to show extra strength.  What do you bid now?[BID pass]
[show NS]
You have nothing further to say so the partnership arrives in a safe contract.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:KJ965.AK843.75.4 ... Q4.QT7.AJ6.AT986 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 2NT Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\S.  So far you know you belong in game, but you don't know which game.  What do you bid first?[BID 2C]
You respond 2\C, natural and forcing the partnership to game.
North now bids his \H suit.
At this point you figurer North for 5 \Ss and 4 \Hs. What should you rebid?[BID 2NT]
You cannot support either of North's Majors, but with a good stopper in the fourth suit you bid 2NT. The game force is still on and North may not pass this bid.
North bids 3\H, indicating that this is also a 5-card suit. What do you rebid now? [BID 4H]
[show NS]
Now you can bid the \H game, knowing there is an 8-card fit.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "6"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:65.AQ953.KQ63.Q9 ... AJT74.KT7.A95.72 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
Pass 1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
What do you open with this hand?[BID 1S]
You opens 1\S and North, responds 2\H. Note that this promises a 5-card or longer \H suit.  (2 of a minor only promises 4+).
What do you rebid?[BID 3H]
Knowing that North has 5, you bid 3\H to confirm the trump suit.
North bids 4\h.  What do you bid now?[BID pass]
[show NS]
North went straight to game, showing a minimum opener and no slam interest.
You are also satisfied to just play at game.
2/1 is a good bidding method, and here, 4\H is a good contract. But you can see that it is not a laydown - there is no bidding system that will always reach 100% contracts. In this hand a 3-3 \D split will provide the 10th trick, or if that fails, taking 2 \S finesses provides a 75% chance of success.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "7"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:AK9652.T983.4.A8 ... 7.AK75.K762.KQT6 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\S.  What do you respond?[BID 2C]
You have 15 HCP, but you only have 4\hs, so you can't bid 2\H (this would promise a 5-card suit).  So instead you bid clubs.  This is natural and game-forcing, but only promises 4+ clubs.
Note that holding two 4-card minors you bid them up-the-line, just as in standard bidding.
North rebids 2\h.  This shows at least 4 hearts.  What do you rebid now?[BID 3H]
Your 3\h bid confirms hearts as trump.  There's no worry partner might pass - we are in a game forcing auction.
North raises to 4\h, showing no slam interest.  What do you bid now?[BID pass]
[show NS]
We don't have enough for slam opposite a minimum opener, so we just pass.
Note North's decision to show the poor 4-card heart suit for their second bid, instead of showing the 6th spade.  In a GF sequence, it's more important to tell about 4 more cards then 1 more card.  North will always have the chance to rebid spades later if there is no heart fit.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "8"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:AK92.AQ983.85.86 ... 875.K4.AQJT7.K97 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1H Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\H - how do you respond?[BID 2D]
North next bids 2\S, showing the other Major suit.  In standard bidding this is a Reverse, showing a strong hand with 5\hs and 4\ss.  But after a 2/1 GF response, North doesn't need extra values to show their 4-card spade suit.  What should you rebid?[BID 2NT]
You assume North to be 4-5 in the Majors, and since you can't support either one, you bid 2NT.
If North actually has 6 \Hs (or 5 \Ss) he would rebid the suit. Your 2NT bid guarantees a stopper in the fourth suit.
[show NS]
North does not have either 6 \Hs or 5 \Ss so he just bids 3NT.  Notice that North never once considered the possibility of passing what might be a misfit - the initial 2/1 response unconditionally forced the partnership to reach a game somewhere.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
