[Auction "S"]
1H Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 4H Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
How do you start this action? [Bid 1H]
You open 1\H and partner responds 2\D.  What do you rebid? [bid 2h]
Partner's 2 over 1 bid sets up a game force.
You have a good-looking hand, but you need to find a trump suit before showing extra strength, so she bids just 2\H.  You are in a game forcing auction, so partner won't pass you.
Partner now jumps to 4\h.  What do you do now? [bid pass]
[show NS]
Partner's jump to 4\h is Fast Arrival - showing a minimum game forcing hand.  Even though we have extra values, this won't be enough for slam opposite 13 or so points.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "15"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:AQ862.T4.K65.K87 ... J.KQJ753.432.Q54 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2H Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\S. What do you respond? [bid 1NT]
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\H in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So we use the forcing 1NT.  North rebids 2\c.   This only promises 3 clubs, so is really just there so we can better describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? [bid 2h]
[show NS]
Now we can bid 2H, and it shows 6+\hs and only 6-10 points. 
North was forced to reply to 1NT, but he is not forced to bid again. With his minimum hand and a tolerance for partner's suit he just passes and the partnership ends up in a reasonable contract.
This hand demonstrates one of the benefits of Forcing 1NT. In standard bidding South's first response would be 2\H, and North would have to bid again, probably 2NT. The partnership might go even higher but in any case would probably not reach a good contract.}

