{[show S]
North opens 1\S. What should you bid? [bid 1NT]
You have 11 points, enough to respond 2\C, (or 2\D), in standard bidding, but not when using 2/1. So you bid 1NT, showing 6-12 points.
North rebids 2\c.  Again, this doesn't promise more than 3\c - it's just leaving room for us to describe our hand with our second bid.  What do we bid now? [bid 2NT]
[show NS]
We know North doesn't have 4 \Hs, so we show our above-minimum hand by bidding 2NT.
North has extra values and raises to 3NT.
North is happy to play Notrump. He assumes we must have something useful in \Ds and bids 3NT.
3NT seems to be a good contract. There are 8 top tricks and possibilities for a ninth winner in either \Ss, \Ds, or, (the best chance), \Cs.}

