{[show S]
North opens 1\H and East Doubles.  What do you bid now? [bid 2c]
[show NS]
After the intervening Takeout Double <b>2/1 is OFF</b>. If you had 10 or more points you would Redouble. So even with only 9 points you can bid 2\C without fear that North will think you have a strong hand.
North also knows everything mentioned above so he passes.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "20"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:QJ2.J2.QJ862.AKJ ... AK98764.KQ7.K73. ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 3S Pass 4C Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
You have a great hand - how will you start the bidding? [bid 1s]
You open 1\S. North responds 2\D, a 2/1 force to game.  What do you bid now? [bid 2s]
You have a big hand, perhaps in the slam range, but first priority is to set a trump suit. So you contend yourself with a rebid of 2\S.  North agrees on trumps by bidding 3\S (not Fast Arrival).  What do you do now? [bid 4\c]
Now you make your slam try by using a Control-showing cue-bid. She bids 4\C, showing first or second round control of the suit (Ace or king, or singleton or void).
North bids 4\s.  What do you do now? [bid pass]
[show NS]
North's next bid would be a control-showing bid of her own - IF SHE HAD ONE. Since she cannot win the first or second round of either red suit she just returns to 4\S. South realizes that they are off two red Aces and passes.
Notice that South did not fall into the Blackwood trap. If you HAD asked for Aces, North would have shown one Ace and South wouldn't know what to do next. She might have figured the odds favored that one Ace being a red one and tried the slam. Moral: Don't use Blackwood when you have a void.}

