Pass Pass 1S Pass 2D Pass 2H Pass 2S Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North passes - what should you open? [bid 1s]
North now bids 2\D. What do you bid now? [bid 2h]
Since North originally passed this is <b>NOT</b> 2/1 Game Force. Instead, it is non-forcing and shows 11 or more points. 
You should show your 4-card \H suit. North gives a preference to 2\S.  What do you do now? [bid pass]
[show NS]
Knowing that North does not have opening strength you pass 2\S.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "24"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:KQT62.A74.84.A85 ... 74.9863.A762.KQ3 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
1S Pass 1NT Pass 2C Pass 2S Pass Pass Pass
{[show S]
North opens 1\S. What do you respond? [bid 1nt]
With 9 points and a doubleton \S you must respond 1NT.   Partner rebids 2\c.  What do you bid now? [bid 2s]
[show NS]
South prefers \C over \S but must allow for the possibility that North has bid a 3-card suit. So South gives a preference to 2\S. This is called a "false preference", but it assures the team of being in at least a 7-card fit. 
North happily passes and the pair lands in a reasonable contract, probably better than 1NT.}

[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Board "25"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:Q6.AKQ972.984.AQ ... AK874.J86.AJ6.93 ..."]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 4C =1= Pass 4D =2= Pass 4NT =3= Pass 5H =4= Pass 5NT =5= Pass 6H =6= Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:control"]
[Note "2:control"]
[Note "3:keycard ask for \h s"]
[Note "4:2 no Q"]
[Note "5:Specific kings ask"]
[Note "6:none below \H s"]
{[show S]
How do you start the bidding? [bid 1s]
You opens 1\S. Partner bids 2\H.   What do you bid now? [bid 3h]
Your priority on your first rebid is to agree trumps if possible. Knowing North has at least a 5-card suit, you raise to 3\H.  You are in a Game Forcing auction, so you know partner will continue bidding.
North now bids 4\c.  What do you bid? [BID 4D]
North's 4\c bid shows first or second round control in clubs, and shows slam interest.  You cooperate by bidding your next control up suit order - 4\d.  This doesn't promise extra values, it's just following partner's path.
North asks for keycards using 1430.  What is your reply? [bid 5H]
You show two keycards without the trump queen.  Partner is excited about this and bids 5NT - what's your bid now? [bid 6H]
Partner's 5NT is asking for specific kings.  Since we don't have any kings lower than the trump suit, we have to bid 6\h.
 and gets two. He decides to find out about Kings, if South happens to have three he will bid 7NT. When South shows just one North settles for 6\H. This should be a good slam, needing only a decent \S break.
[show NS]}

